                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d435">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 435.</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">S. L. Phelps</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-02-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">February</hi> 28, 1885</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 110.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your Nos.
                    203 and 204.</p>
                <p>The firm tone which has characterized your presentation of the case of the
                    murdered American citizen, Owen Young, is particularly satisfactory to this
                    Government, which can do no less than insist on the fullest measure of justice
                    from Peru, in any and all aspects of the case.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FKED’K T. FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
